ducation?  Who will step up to the plate and start this ball rolling?  Will they go down in history with the best parent award for taking the bull by the horn?  Will there children be taken care of for being the examples?  It's a tough subject and unless someone with great influence can create an army of parents to battle this fight the fight will be to difficult and the sacrifice will be too large for the one parent that tries to make a difference.  I am not saying this in opposition to your article Kristin, I am saying this because that is one of the strong thoughts in the back of the minds of people who have a choice. I did send my children to public school in a lower middle class neighborhood and I worked with my children and their teachers with terrific results.  Thank you for your article.  It is never a bad time to ruffle feathers over this subject! "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1176" language="en" documentId="2919" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="I was blind but now I see" date="Aug 29, 2013 8:01PM" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://living.msn.com/family-parenting/the-family-room-blog-post?post=ab228ffc-1e99-4b37-a7b8-0b6a4c3fb240" topic="public-private-schools" thumbsUp="3" thumbsDown="0" origId="2919" notes="" title="Is it wrong to send kids to private school?"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1176"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39"/></xmi:XMI>